        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer220456518" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1878058459842147276"><b>Re-read for the second time. I had forgotten how much action there was in this book as I hadn&apos;t read it since its first publication in 1995, when I was introduced to Agent Pendergast.</b><br/><br/>The first part of the book starts out a little slow as it provides the back drop for the story and then the last half of the story the action begins. <br/><br/>What better way to spend the day at a museum without a care in the world until you find out there is a creature loose in the place and no one knows where it could be o</span>
  <span id="freeText1878058459842147276" style="display:none"><b>Re-read for the second time. I had forgotten how much action there was in this book as I hadn't read it since its first publication in 1995, when I was introduced to Agent Pendergast.</b><br /><br />The first part of the book starts out a little slow as it provides the back drop for the story and then the last half of the story the action begins. <br /><br />What better way to spend the day at a museum without a care in the world until you find out there is a creature loose in the place and no one knows where it could be or where it could strike next. This is no ordinary creature either as it is very intelligent and even has the capability to open doors. It also likes humans, but not to get friendly with them, but to add them to its snack list. <br /><br /><b>The book has suspense, mystery, horror, and a little gore thrown in for good measure!</b><br /><br />I am still giving the book five stars like I did before and I will be continuing the series.</span>
